    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Brighton Weddy Morg 14th Augst</p>
      <p>Dearest W. I have nothing very momentous to say, but I do not like to leave you even a day unnecessarily without a line from your Thrush.</p>
      <p>Our weather is lamentable, most dispiriting, &amp; much against me. It is continual rain &amp; winds. No boating possible; but I manage the swimming daily, very perseveringly. I get to enjoy these immersions more &amp; more, &amp; certainly I think it is the most invigorating, salubrious &amp;</p>
      <p>exhilarating habit possible, &amp; will make Ashley far more beneficial to me than hitherto; especially if I can really become an independant &amp; skilful swimmer. I make some progress; but slowly. Perseverance will do the business, I feel no doubt.</p>
      <p>I hope you will approve my swimming costume now. I have two varieties. One is what I may term a complete skin, of black camlet Trousers &amp; jacket all in one. I found a woman here who makes these dresses for swimming ladies, taking one's proper measures. It is not considered safe to have anything approaching to a petticoat or loose thing round the body, I find; since the middle of the person is thereby</p>
      <p>buoyed up, &amp; then one is turned or tilted over with the head under. Therefore ladies either have these complete black skins, or else a pair of close black trousers, &amp; a Guernsey Jacket.</p>
      <p>I have both costumes, so as to choose either at my pleasure. Also a pair of very strong common leather half boots, merely for use in the water, to save the feet &amp; ankles.--</p>
      <p>Some other ladies are now learning to swim of the same two watermen (brothers) whom I employ for boating &amp; batheing; but I have nothing to do with these pupils; or with any one.</p>
      <p>We were all delighted yesterday with the exhibition of horsemanship, gymnastics, &amp; animals; especially with the elephant, who-- poor fellow-- exceeds in intelligence &amp; gentleness anything I could have conceived.</p>
      <p>You would like this exhibition. It is far from being a mere idle amusement, but is really philosophically interesting &amp; curious. The equitation most beautiful. One man acted Phaeton, driving or rather riding four fiery rampant gallopping steeds in exact imitation of the representations of that personage.</p>
      <p>I continue to mend, by slow degrees.</p>
      <p>Delighted at Drummond's invitation.</p>
